  "title": "Toward a Field Theory",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "224cfcc16d0145d3",
      "text": "Kurt Lewin's field theory of learning, also known as Lewin's theory of change, is a psychological model that describes how an individual's behavior is influenced by the interaction between their personal characteristics and the environment in which they are located. Lewin proposed that behavior is a function of the person and the environment, and that individuals are motivated to reduce the gap between their current state and a desired state. He also emphasized the importance of understanding the dynamic nature of behavior and the need for active experimentation in the process of change. This theory has been influential in the field of organizational behavior and change management.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "2759728d4a7571e3",
      "text": "Kurt Lewin was a psychologist born in Poland in the late 1800s. He studied psychology in Germany and later emigrated to America. Working closely with Gestalt psychologists, he developed Field Theory and other ideas on change, education, and learning. [https://practicalpie.com/lewins-field-theory/ source]"
    },
